            <h2>Why Meal Prep is Essential for Fitness and Health</h2>
            <p>Meal preparation is one of the most effective habits you can build to support your health, fitness, and financial goals. By planning and cooking your meals in advance, you eliminate the daily friction of deciding what to eat. This significantly reduces the likelihood of ordering takeout or reaching for processed convenience foods when you are tired, hungry, or stressed.</p>
            <p>Consistency is the key to any diet, whether you are trying to lose body fat, build muscle, or simply improve your overall nutrition. Having a fridge stocked with pre-portioned, macro-friendly meals guarantees that you hit your nutritional targets day after day with minimal mental effort.</p>

            <h2>Pro Tips for Successful Meal Prepping</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Invest in Good Containers:</strong> High-quality, BPA-free plastic or glass containers with tight-fitting, leak-proof lids are essential. Glass is preferred if you microwave your meals frequently, as it doesn't absorb odors or stain.</li>
                <li><strong>Start Small:</strong> If you are new to meal prepping, do not try to prep 21 meals for the week on your first try. Start by prepping just your lunches for Monday to Wednesday. Once you master that, you can scale up.</li>
                <li><strong>Sauces on the Side:</strong> To prevent food from getting soggy (especially salads or breaded items), keep your dressings and sauces in small, separate containers and add them right before eating.</li>
                <li><strong>Use the Freezer:</strong> If you get bored of eating the same thing for four days straight, freeze half of your prep. You can then rotate meals from previous weeks to keep your diet interesting.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Common Meal Prep Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
            <p>One major mistake beginners make is ignoring food safety. Cooked food should not sit at room temperature for more than two hours. Once your food is cooked and portioned, let it cool slightly and then immediately transfer it to the refrigerator or freezer.</p>
            <p>Another common pitfall is overcomplicating recipes. Save the complex, multi-step culinary masterpieces for a relaxed weekend dinner. For meal prep, focus on simple, whole foods that can be batched efficiently: roasted vegetables, baked proteins, and boiled grains.</p>
